Important Context to Keep in Mind
Public Repositories: If you host this code on a platform like GitHub in a public repository, you are still the owner. However, GitHub’s Terms of Service allow others to view and fork your repository (copying it to their own profile within the platform). If you want to prevent even that, you should use a Private Repository.

The "Look but don't Touch" Reality: Even with this license, if the code is public, people will read it. This license gives you the legal ground to sue or send a DMCA takedown notice if you find your code elsewhere, but it doesn't physically lock the "copy" button on their keyboard.

Fair Use: In some jurisdictions, small snippets might still be used under "Fair Use" for educational or transformative purposes, regardless of your license.